[ProMED thanks Viki Hansen-Landis for submitting these travel advisories. If any reader has further information on the Rwandan travel advisory, ProMED would welcome that information, particularly in response to the questions raised by the submitter in her post. With travel advisories being enacted by a country neighboring the DRC, one would think it is time for WHO to declare a public health emergency of international concern.

The upgraded CDC travel alert for the DRC is level 2, practice enhanced precautions. See https://wwwnc.cdc.gov/travel/notices/alert/ebola-democratic-republic-of-the-congo

"Key points:
- There is an outbreak of Ebola in the North Kivu (Kivu Nord) and Ituri provinces in the northeastern part of the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC).
- The outbreak is in a part of the country identified by the US State Department as a "do not travel" zone because of armed group activity and major outbreaks of violence targeting civilians.
- The armed conflict and violence in the outbreak area are hampering response activities including early identification of cases, and monitoring of "contacts" (people who may have been exposed to Ebola).
- Travelers to this area could be infected with Ebola if they come into contact with an infected person's blood or other body fluids.
- Travelers should seek medical care immediately if they develop fever, headache, body aches, sore throat, diarrhea, weakness, vomiting, stomach pain, rash, or red eyes during or after travel."
- Mod.LK]

